review_blob:
A cloudy gold with a fluffy white head...Sweet and tart aroma of citrus/apple.  Each sip blossoms with an array of spices and fruits.  Nutmeg/cloves, citrus/banana. 
This is a tasty affordable beer!  Im not usually a fan of Hefeweizens, but this one is smooth and balanced.  If youre getting beers at Trader Joes....I definitely recommend this one!

Pillowy white head.  Sweep hoppy aroma.  Almost tastless aside a slightly sour fermented backdrop that is just enough to let you know youre not drinking a club soda.  A snap of tasty hops jump out towards the end of each sip, but its brief...very brief.  Would be great for a college kid to throw in the line up somewhere between the 3rd or 4th Bud Light.

Soul searchingly dark with a thin tan head that dissipates rather quickly.  Sweet well rounded beginning with good chocolate flavor that settles into a warm roasty flavor that really fills the palate and is very pleasing.  Long bittersweet finish that leaves you craving the next sip
   Very good brew...not a usual fan of black ales or stouts, but this exceeded my expectations by far.
Nice head with the hearty round flavor of a good oatmeal stout.  This was complimented with a subtle yet present aroma and flavor of a dark roast coffee.  Very good!

I usually prefer beers that have depth and a well orchestrated harmony of flavors...this is why I rarely get pilsners or lagers.  I have yet to have a lager that exceeds my expectations as a simpleton guzzling beer that goes great with pizza (which,I did have it with pizza.)  This beer really didnt raise itself above that expectation.  However, with that said, this was a very enjoyable lager!  It certainly does not punish your tongue like almost all macro brewed lagers....no it humbly and quietly serves its purpose to the best of its ability, and that is to make pizza and football that much better!!

This was a mediocre beer for me.  Its listed under stouts, but it is really a black ale.  It feels like drinking a flat watered down coke at first.  However, once the beer settles on the palate it surprises you with a bite of flavor.  The flavor and aroma resemble burnt coffee before beer, but not entirely bad.  If it was labeled as a kind of coffee ale, I wouldnt like it any more, but the flavor and aroma would seem less accidental.
